<subSubSection id="C305657F157B2A38D5D4FB124B33FEC2" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="758" pageId="30" pageNumber="757" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA036F4157B2A39D5D4FB124ABAF994" blockId="30.[178,1086,1257,1542]" pageId="30" pageNumber="757">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Length 
<quantity id="4CE79B11157B2A39D485FB114B71FB6D" box="[483,580,1257,1279]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.84" pageId="30" pageNumber="757" unit="mm" value="5.84">5.84 mm</quantity>
. Body shiny, yellowish-red, sides and posterior margin of the elytra brown, antennae brown with the three basal antennomeres yellowish-red, legs yellowish-red. Second antennomere shorter than the first, third longer than the second, fourth as long as wide, fifth to tenth transverse. Eyes longer than the postocular region in dorsal view. Fore-body devoid of reticulation, that of the abdomen very transverse and very superficial, but on the sixth free tergite very transverse and evident. Puncturation of the head evident and not very dense, absent on a narrow longitudinal median band. Puncturation of the pronotum strong and denser on either side of the median line, sparse on the rest of the surface, that of the abdomen fine and sparse. There is a salient tubercle between the antennae. Spermatheca: 
<figureCitation id="13242A71157B2A39D655FA084ABAF994" box="[819,911,1520,1542]" captionStart="Figs 181-194" captionStartId="63.[178,218,1424,1444]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,220,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-2@63.[178,1085,220,1016]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="Figs 181-194: Aedeagus in lateral and ventral view, spermatheca, sixth free urotergum of male. (181-182): Drusilla sabahensis nov.sp.; (183): Drusilla profunda nov.sp.; (184): Drusilla borneoclara nov.sp.; (185-188): Drusilla rougemontiana nov.sp.; (189-191): Drusilla danumensis nov.sp.; (192-194): Drusilla borneoapicalis nov.sp. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5335503" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5335503/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="757">Fig. 184.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036F4157B2A39D5D4F9EE4D08F9DB" blockId="30.[178,1086,1558,1609]" pageId="30" pageNumber="757">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: The habitus of the new species is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4D77157B2A39D142F9EF4898F9DB" authority="(CAMERON, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="CAMERON" baseAuthorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Drusilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="757" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aerea">
<emphasis id="B96BEAE6157B2A39D142F9EF49DEF9DB" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="757">D. aerea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF8E4B05157B2A39D59DF9CB4893F9DB" author="CAMERON M" box="[251,422,1587,1609]" pageId="30" pageNumber="757" pagination="338 - 360" refId="ref32122" refString="CAMERON M. (1933): Staphylinidae (Col.) from Mount Kinabalu. - Journal of the Federated Malay States Museums 17: 338 - 360." type="journal article" year="1933">CAMERON, 1933</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
also from Borneo, but the spermatheca is different. The proxi-
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036F4157A2A38D5D4FF2248F4FE9C" blockId="31.[178,1085,218,270]" pageId="31" pageNumber="758">
mal portion of the spermatheca of the new species is bisinuate, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4D77157A2A38D6DAFF234D23FF62" baseAuthorityName="CAMERON" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[956,1046,219,240]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Drusilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="758" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aerea">
<emphasis id="B96BEAE6157A2A38D6DAFF234D23FF62" box="[956,1046,219,240]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="758">D. aerea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the same portion is rectilinear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036F4157A2A38D5D4FEE64B33FEC2" blockId="31.[178,1085,285,336]" pageId="31" pageNumber="758">E t y m o l o g y: The name of the new species &quot;Borneo pale&quot; refers to the mostly yellowish-red colour of the body.</paragraph>
